{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658648"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:52:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20806"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20806"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13681"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96110"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13681"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78838"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"11583"},{"type":"tags","id":"12640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32940"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96110"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA woman presents with fever, rash, thrombocytopenia and elevated liver enzymes. Blood smear reveals gram-negative coccobacilli within endothelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which this infectious agent causes cell injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of immune complexes in vessel walls","Intracellular replication causing endothelial damage","Inhibition of oxidative phosphorylation","Direct invasion and consumption of host cell cytoplasm","Production of exotoxins that form membrane pores"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is consistent with Rocky Mountain spotted fever, caused by \u003Cem\u003ERickettsia rickettsii\u003C/em\u003E. The primary mechanism of cell injury is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintracellular replication causing endothelial damage\u003C/strong\u003E. Rickettsiae are obligate intracellular bacteria that primarily infect endothelial cells. After entering the cell, they escape from the phagosome, replicate in the cytoplasm, and eventually cause cell lysis. This endothelial damage leads to increased vascular permeability, causing the characteristic rash, as well as activation of inflammatory and coagulation cascades.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect invasion and consumption of host cell cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of certain protozoan parasites like amoebae, not rickettsiae, which replicate within cells but do not directly consume cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of exotoxins that form membrane pores\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is typical of certain bacteria like \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (alpha-toxin) or \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E (streptolysin O), but rickettsiae do not produce pore-forming toxins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of immune complexes in vessel walls\u003C/strong\u003E - While immune-mediated damage can occur in some infections, the primary pathology in rickettsial infections is direct endothelial cell damage from intracellular replication\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of oxidative phosphorylation\u003C/strong\u003E - This mechanism is seen with certain toxins like cyanide or antimycin A, but is not the primary mechanism for rickettsial pathogenesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gram-negative coccobacilli seen within endothelial cells on blood smear are characteristic of rickettsial infections. The clinical triad of fever, headache, and rash, along with laboratory findings of thrombocytopenia and elevated liver enzymes, strongly supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Infectious agents cause cell injury through diverse mechanisms including direct cytopathic effects, production of toxins, and induction of host immune responses.","Viruses can cause cell injury by disrupting host cell protein synthesis, inducing apoptosis, or triggering cytolytic immune responses.","Bacterial toxins can damage cell membranes, inhibit protein synthesis, or disrupt cellular signaling pathways.","Protozoan parasites can cause cell injury through direct invasion, consumption of cellular contents, or obstruction of vital structures."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 2; page 36."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78838"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78838"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T23:14:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T23:19:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13681"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96110"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"